{"ts": "2026-06-08T04:57:02.987149+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "I have enough information to provide a thorough answer. Here is the summary:\n\n---\n\n## Runtime Profiles\n\nThe repository (`spring-boot-java-template`) documents **five runtime profiles** in its README, each serving a distinct deployment/development stage:\n\n| Profile | Purpose |\n|---------|---------|\n| **`local`** | Configures an environment that can be developed even when the network is disconnected (fully offline). |\n| **`local-dev`** | Allows connecting to the **DEV** environment from a developer’s local machine. |\n| **`dev`** | Used for deploying to the **Development** environment. |\n| **`staging`** | Used for deploying to the **Staging** (pre-production) environment. |\n| **`live`** | Used for deploying to the **Live** (production) environment. |\n\nAdditionally, the **core** module’s readme notes: *“Ignore runtime profile differences and report only the local profile setup.”* — meaning the executable `core:core-api` module focuses on/assumes the local profile for its default setup.\n\n---\n\n## Recommended Developer Setup for Lint & Local Testing\n\n### 1. Linting\n\n- **Mechanism:** The project uses [Spring Java Format](https://github.com/spring-io/spring-javaformat) via the `io.spring.javaformat` Gradle plugin, configured in `lint.gradle`.\n- **Manual lint check:** Run `./gradlew checkFormat` (or `gradlew.bat checkFormat` on Windows).\n- **Pre‑commit hook (recommended):**  \n  Execute the following command once to make lint run on every commit:\n  ```\n  git config core.hookspath .githooks\n  ```\n  The hook script (`.githooks/pre-commit`) simply invokes `./gradlew checkFormat`.\n- **IntelliJ IDEA integration:**  \n  To apply the same formatting rules inside the IDE, install the Spring Java Format plugin and follow the [official IntelliJ setup guide](https://github.com/spring-io/spring-javaformat#intellij-idea).\n\n### 2. Running Tests Locally\n\n- **Test framework:** JUnit 5 (JUnit Platform), executed through Gradle.\n- **Available test tasks (defined in `build.gradle`):**\n\n| Task | Tag filter | Purpose |\n|------|------------|---------|\n| `test` (default) | Excludes `develop`, `restdocs` | The main CI test suite. |\n| `unitTest` | Excludes `develop`, `context`, `restdocs` | Fast, dependency‑free unit tests (single feature). |\n| `contextTest` | Includes `context` | Integration tests that require a Spring context. |\n| `restDocsTest` | Includes `restdocs` | Generates Asciidoc documentation from Spring REST Docs. |\n| `developTest` | Includes `develop` | Tests **not** intended for CI; useful for work‑in‑progress test code. |\n\n- **Running tests:** Use `./gradlew <taskName>`, e.g.:\n  - `./gradlew test` – runs the standard CI suite\n  - `./gradlew unitTest` – runs only fast unit tests\n  - `./gradlew contextTest` – runs integration tests\n- **IntelliJ IDEA recommendation (for running tests):**  \n  Set:  \n  `Build, Execution, Deployment → Build Tools → Gradle → Run tests using → IntelliJ IDEA`  \n  This allows running test code directly from the IDE with less friction.\n\n### 3. Continuous Integration (CI) Setup\n\nThe file `.github/workflows/ci.yml` shows the CI pipeline:\n1. Check out the code\n2. Set up JDK 21 (Adoptium)\n3. Run `./gradlew checkFormat` (lint)\n4. Run `./gradlew test` (the default test suite)\n\nThis mirrors the recommended local workflow: **lint first, then test**.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1401, "prompt_tokens": 9749, "total_tokens": 11150, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 560, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 9344}, "prompt_cache_hit_tokens": 9344, "prompt_cache_miss_tokens": 405}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "deepseek-v4-pro", "system_fingerpr